<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1436,935,1717]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,286,935,960]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Etymology.</emphasis>
Latin, 
<emphasis box="[380,467,935,960]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">abyssus</emphasis>
, deep sea, plus - 
<emphasis box="[682,742,937,960]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">oecia</emphasis>
, a common suffix for tubuliporine 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Busk" authorityYear="1852" box="[1179,1337,935,960]" class="Stenolaemata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclostomata" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="order">Cyclostomata</taxonomicName>
. Gender feminine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1436,935,1717]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1007,1032]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Colony erect to suberect, flabellate to subcalyciform, supported by founding zooids and additional pillars derived from autozooids. No basal kenozooids. Peristomes produced from frontal surface. Gonozooid simple, reniform, not pierced by zooidal peristomes, ooeciostome narrow. Ancestrular zooid suberect with squat imperforate protoecium.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1436,935,1717]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1151,1176]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Remarks.</emphasis>
The simple form of the gonozooid suggests inclusion in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Grischenko &amp; Gordon &amp; Melnik" authorityYear="2018" box="[999,1181,1151,1176]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Oncousoeciidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclostomatida" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="family">Oncousoeciidae</taxonomicName>
, used to accommodate tubuliporine cyclostomes having simple gonozooids with terminal cylindrical ooeciostomes (
<bibRefCitation pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refId="ref37150" refString="Taylor, P. D. &amp; Zaton, M. (2008) Taxonomy of the bryozoan genera Oncousoecia, Microeciella and Eurystrotos (Cyclostomata: Oncousoeciidae). Journal of Natural History, 42, 2557 - 2574. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222930802277640" type="journal article">Taylor &amp; Zato≈Ñ 2008</bibRefCitation>
). Compared to 
<taxonomicName authority="Grischenko &amp; Gordon &amp; Melnik, 2018" authorityName="Grischenko &amp; Gordon &amp; Melnik" authorityYear="2018" box="[383,509,1223,1248]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Oncousoeciidae" genus="Abyssoecia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclostomatida" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[383,509,1223,1248]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Abyssoecia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[516,594,1223,1248]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[516,594,1223,1248]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Canu, 1918" authorityName="Canu" authorityYear="1918" box="[727,1010,1224,1248]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Diastoporidae" genus="Oncousoecia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclostomatida" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[727,873,1224,1247]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Oncousoecia</emphasis>
Canu, 1918
</taxonomicName>
have wholly encrusting colonies with pluriserial branches, and both differ from 
<taxonomicName authority="Taylor &amp; Sequeiros, 1982" authorityName="Taylor &amp; Sequeiros" authorityYear="1982" box="[624,1068,1260,1285]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Oncousoeciidae" genus="Microeciella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclostomatida" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[624,766,1260,1285]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Microeciella</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[774,1068,1260,1285]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refId="ref37008" refString="Taylor, P. D. &amp; Sequeiros, L. (1982) Toarcian bryozoans from Belchite in north-east Spain. Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), Geology, 37, 117 - 129." type="journal article">Taylor &amp; Sequeiros, 1982</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, in which species are multiserial and flabellate to circular. The ancestrula is wholly adnate in species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Canu" authorityYear="1918" box="[985,1131,1296,1319]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Diastoporidae" genus="Oncousoecia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclostomatida" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[985,1131,1296,1319]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Oncousoecia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Taylor &amp; Sequeiros" authorityYear="1982" box="[1192,1334,1295,1320]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Oncousoeciidae" genus="Microeciella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclostomatida" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1192,1334,1295,1320]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Microeciella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Among other putative oncousoeciids, 
<taxonomicName authority="d'Orbigny, 1853" authorityName="d'Orbigny" authorityYear="1853" box="[510,834,1332,1357]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Oncousoeciidae" genus="Filisparsa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclostomatida" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[510,625,1332,1357]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Filisparsa</emphasis>
d‚ÄôOrbigny, 1853
</taxonomicName>
differs in having erect, dichotomously branching flattened stems and 
<taxonomicName authority="d'Orbigny, 1853" authorityName="d'Orbigny" authorityYear="1853" box="[385,724,1367,1392]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Diastoporidae" genus="Discosparsa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclostomatida" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[385,525,1369,1392]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Discosparsa</emphasis>
d‚ÄôOrbigny, 1853
</taxonomicName>
differs in having umbrelliform, radially symmetrical circular colonies supported by a central stalk, elongate gonozooid (pierced by autozooidal peristomes in at least one species), and elevated subcolonies from the primary colony.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1436,935,1717]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
Among living species, the semi-erect ancestrula is exceptional for the family; no information is available concerning the ancestrula in erect Mesozoic taxa that may be related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Grischenko &amp; Gordon &amp; Melnik" authorityYear="2018" box="[986,1169,1511,1536]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Oncousoeciidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclostomatida" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="family">Oncousoeciidae</taxonomicName>
. Interestingly, although colony form is very different in the species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Grischenko &amp; Gordon &amp; Melnik, 2018" authorityName="Grischenko &amp; Gordon &amp; Melnik" authorityYear="2018" box="[726,874,1548,1573]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Incertae" genus="Pandanipora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclostomata" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[726,874,1548,1573]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Pandanipora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[887,972,1548,1573]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[887,972,1548,1573]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Grischenko &amp; Gordon &amp; Melnik, 2018" authorityName="Grischenko &amp; Gordon &amp; Melnik" authorityYear="2018" box="[992,1122,1549,1572]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Incertae" genus="Orectopora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclostomata" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[992,1122,1549,1572]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Orectopora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1135,1220,1548,1573]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1135,1220,1548,1573]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Grischenko &amp; Gordon &amp; Melnik, 2018" authorityName="Grischenko &amp; Gordon &amp; Melnik" authorityYear="2018" box="[1241,1382,1549,1572]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Plagioeciidae" genus="Discantenna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclostomatida" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[1241,1382,1549,1572]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Discantenna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Grischenko &amp; Gordon &amp; Melnik, 2018" authorityName="Grischenko &amp; Gordon &amp; Melnik" authorityYear="2018" box="[151,277,1583,1608]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Oncousoeciidae" genus="Abyssoecia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclostomatida" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[151,277,1583,1608]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Abyssoecia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[286,367,1583,1608]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[286,367,1583,1608]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
described herein, the semi-erect to erect ancestrula is very similar, perhaps suggesting either environmental or phylogenetic correlation or both. Erect or semi-erect ancestrulae prior to this study were considered to characterise Articulata and Cancellata, although in one Jurassic species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Taylor &amp; Sequeiros" authorityYear="1982" box="[1244,1386,1655,1680]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Oncousoeciidae" genus="Microeciella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyclostomatida" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1244,1386,1655,1680]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Microeciella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the ancestrular tube is initially semi-erect before descending back down to the substratum (
<bibRefCitation box="[1127,1415,1692,1717]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refId="ref37008" refString="Taylor, P. D. &amp; Sequeiros, L. (1982) Toarcian bryozoans from Belchite in north-east Spain. Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), Geology, 37, 117 - 129." type="journal article">Taylor &amp; Sequeiros 1982</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
